comments.text: Ah sorry, should have been more specific in the details. I use Simplify3D which allows multiple extruder processes (not sure if others will allow this, I only have experience with S3D). So what I do is create process 1 and have it stop at a certain height using tool/extruder 1. During this time, the second tool is cool until the last 2 layers, at which point it heats up. I create a second process for tool 2, which will start where tool 1 left off, and tool 1 will then cool off. Hope that makes sense. To me, it's a lot easier doing it this way than creating 2 parts and trying to align them.
comments.author: Jaydawgx7

comments.text:
Thanks, that makes sense now. That is basically the process people use to dual extrude using a single extruder except you don't have to change the filament. I too use simplify 3d and im not sure how much experience you have with dual extrusion, but if you create an object with 2 stl files (one for each color) you can print multiple colors on the same later. For example, if you look at this coaster I made, you can see the 2 files. You just add them both to simplify3d, then run the dual extrusion wizard and it will combine them. I have also posted a tool change script which can be added to the process that will allow the extruder to cool when switching colors to help avoid any oozing of the wrong color during your print. This does make the print take longer as it keeps stopping to cool off, but it's worth it.

description.text:
A "Bender" head filament guide for side feeding filament on an Original Prusa MK2, it fits a specific hexagon hole on the top of the Z Axis top bracket. This will probably not work for any other printer (unless you are lucky enough to have a hexagon sized just right).

Add some bender flair to your MK2!

I like to print from the side of my Prusa MK2 as I get a little nervous with a new spool on top. I tried to use some other thingiverse filament guides that attach to the Prusa but using those and printing from the side can cause the filament to catch on various parts.

I did not want something that attached to the top frame, and I noticed the hexagon hole. Perfect.

Notes:

On my Prusa the Hexagon on the right Z axis top bracket (the one I use this on) is slightly bigger than the hexagon on the left. I am not sure if this is just a printing issue at Prusa or designed it that way.. So, you may need to fiddle with size a bit for your MK2.

This sits firmly in the open hexagon and does not affect the Z Axis travel.

Make sure the guide hole does not have burs that would catch or cut your filaments. If the hexagon does not immediately fit, you can trim the bottom edges down for a perfect tight fit.

Since I needed a small and cheap Mini ITX computer case I designed one using boxmaker and some Inkscape magic for the ventilation holes.The box displayed on the pictures has been customized for a local elementary school by adding their logo on the front panel. The entire case was designed to be cut out of a single 600 mm x 300 mm sheet of 3 mm thick MDF

The case will hold a standard Mini ITX motherboard with either an onboard power supply or a picoPSU with a DC input. It also features mounting holes for a 2.5" drive, but make sure that this will fit with your motherboard. The ventilation holes are optimized for the motherboards I used, so you might want to check the optimal placement of those holes depending on your hardware.

you will also need the following hardware :

  • a power button (and you might need to modify the hole in the front for your button)
  • 8 x M3x6 screws for the motherboard (add 4 more for the hard drive if needed)
  • 4 x M3x10mm standoffs

Just cut it out and assemble the case. Be careful when placing the rear IO plate because the wood on the top is rather thin. You can glue 3 feet together to make a sturdy foot or you can cut it out of a thicker piece of scrap material.

description.text:
"Resumen en castellano al final"

For those who doesn't know The Antikythera Mechanism is an artifact found in 1900 in the coast of the greek Antikythera island, once studied it was dated to be from 200 B.C. being the most ancient computer to be known so far.

This model is a interpretation of that machine in order to 3d print it 100% in 3D.

We want to make it clear that this model does not pretend to be an accurate and historical reconstruction of the Antikythera mechanism, just a project to share and divulge.

For more info (and Spanish translation):
http://kirolab.blogspot.com.es/2016/10/interpretacion-del-mecanismo-de.html
http://kirolab.blogspot.com.es/2016/10/interpretacion-del-mecanismo-de_11.html

UPDATE!
-Added the sun gears, b1-b2-b3, with the sun axis, and internal axis (for moon gears later on).
-Added the washers and the sun dial.

UPDATE 2!
-Added the C and L gear, the two first sets of gears directly conected to the sun gear, both with their axis and their washers (wich are identical but for keeping everything in order they have their own file).
-Checked some minor errors and may be an update for at least 2 files shortly (ANT_BOX_MIDDLE_FULL.stl and ANT_BOX_INSIDE_3.stl).

UPDATE 3!
-Added the (D1, D2) and (M1, M2, M3) gears.
*M2 is one of the smallest gears, it will be better to print it with a 0,2 nozzle, but a really slow printing time should do with 0,4
-Fixed "ANT_BOX_INSIDE_3", "ANT_BOX_MIDDLE_FULL", "ANTI_MIDDLE_CUT_1"
-Apologies for the delay, we are having much work lately and we are not able to properly check all the gears and construcction.

UPDATE 4!
-Minor changes and fixes for some files.
-Grouped some pieces in one file for better order.

UPDATE 5!
-Added F gear, all ready to upload moon gear set.

UPDATE 6!
-Added Moon gear set (finally):
This set includes, moon main gear, moon support, K1-K2 gears, E1-E2-E5-E6 gears, and moon dial (wich goes on small sun axis)
At this point you will have allmost finished the Antikythera machine and it's time to check that everything fits properly.
Moon gear is the most complex set in the whole mechanism since it has to move with 4 differents gears (B3, D2, M3, F2) and its has it's own gear system inside.

description.text:
A remix of ulflindestrom's ultri leg. I broke it up into 2 pieces, saving printing time to get it flying again. The leg cross brace has been thickened and printing it on the side prevents the shearing force when you scrape the ground, as it changes the orientation of the layers. Instead of shearing the leg like the original it will break at the joint where you glue it. This means that only more glue is needed to get flying again. Comment any criticisms or further improvements that can be made as I am new to CAD and am willing to learn from my mistakes.

Edit: Printed at 0.2mm layer height with 80% fill using either blue PLA or natural ABS. Had to use a brim on the ABS to prevent warping. In hindsight a raft with a gap of 0.2mm for the first layer would have prevented the messy print from cutting the brim away!

Full credit to ulflindestrom for his original design and for the awesome Ultri-copter!
